EP  - 589
VL  - 86
IS  - 2
KW  - Networks
KW  - productivity
KW  - supply chains
KW  - size distribution
KW  - input–output structure
KW  - economic growth
KW  - ideas
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA10731
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Individual producers exhibit enormous heterogeneity in many dimensions. This paper develops a theory in which the network structure of production?who buys inputs from whom?forms endogenously. Entrepreneurs produce using labor and exactly one intermediate input; the key decision is which other entrepreneur's good to use as an input. Their choices collectively determine the economy's equilibrium input?output structure, generating large differences in size and shaping both individual and aggregate productivity. When the elasticity of output to intermediate inputs in production is high, star suppliers emerge endogenously. This raises aggregate productivity as, in equilibrium, more supply chains are routed through higher-productivity techniques.
ER  - 

